  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>In the United States alone, roughly 40 million people take a statin every day. Most of them have never had a heart attack. Most of them never will. For the roughly half of those patients who are considered low cardiovascular risk — no prior event, no diabetes, no family history that would make a cardiologist sit forward — the drug they swallow each morning reduces their absolute chance of a major cardiovascular event by somewhere between one and two percentage points over a decade. Not one to two percent per year. One to two percent, total, over ten years. The number that appears in most patient conversations — the 25 to 35 percent risk reduction that sounds like a near-miracle — describes the same drug. Both figures are real. Only one is routinely shared.</p>
</section>

<section id="how-the-numbers-work" class="reveal">
  <h2>Part I: What the Evidence Actually Shows</h2>
  <p>The distinction between relative and absolute risk reduction is not a statistical technicality. It is the central arithmetic of how a genuinely effective drug for sick people got quietly repositioned as a preventive for healthy ones.</p>
  <p>Here is how it works. Suppose a low-risk population has a 4% chance of a major cardiovascular event over five years. A drug that reduces that rate to 3% has produced a 1 percentage point absolute risk reduction. It has also produced a 25% relative risk reduction — because 3 is 25% less than 4. Drug promoters, and guidelines that lean on drug promoters' data, prefer the second number. It is larger. It implies transformation. A 1% absolute improvement implies that 99 out of 100 patients took a medication for five years and received no measurable cardiovascular benefit from it.</p>
  <p>For low-risk primary prevention, the real-world figures are not far from that. The Number Needed to Treat — the number of patients who must take a statin for several years to prevent one cardiovascular event — runs into the hundreds for this population. The 2022 viewpoint in <em>JAMA Internal Medicine</em> by researchers without industry ties argued that for low-risk patients, harms are systematically underestimated and benefits routinely overstated in precisely this way, and called for communicating absolute risk reduction as the baseline expectation in clinical practice. That this constitutes a radical suggestion — that patients should be told the actual number — is worth sitting with for a moment.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal">
  <p>"98.8% of patients in low-risk primary prevention take a statin for five years and get no measurable cardiovascular benefit from it. Both numbers describe the same drug. Only one appears in most patient conversations."</p>
