<section id="risk-explainer" class="reveal">
  <h2>Relative vs. Absolute Risk: A Worked Example</h2>
  <p><strong>The setup:</strong> A healthy 55-year-old has a 4% chance of a major cardiovascular event over the next five years.</p>
  <p><strong>After statin therapy:</strong> That risk falls to 3%.</p>
  <p><strong>Relative risk reduction:</strong> 25% — the figure in the drug's marketing and often in clinical guidelines.</p>
  <p><strong>Absolute risk reduction:</strong> 1 percentage point — the figure rarely mentioned in the consultation room.</p>
  <p><strong>What it means:</strong> 100 patients take the drug for five years. 99 of them would not have had an event anyway. One avoids it because of the drug. The other 99 received the side-effect risk with no cardiovascular return. This is not an argument against statins. It is an argument for saying both numbers out loud.</p>
</section>

<section id="side-effects-undercount" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Side-Effect Accounting Problem</h2>
  <p>Ask a cardiologist how often statins cause muscle pain, and if they're working from industry-sponsored trial data, they'll say somewhere between 1 and 5 percent of patients. Ask a rheumatologist working in a clinic full of people who've been on statins for a decade, and the answer will be different. Real-world observational data and independent analyses consistently report myalgia rates of 10 to 15 percent — three to ten times higher than the blinded-trial figure. The discrepancy has a straightforward explanation: blinded randomized trials are designed to control for nocebo effects and reporting bias, which tends to suppress adverse event rates; clinicians and patients in the real world are not blinded, and neither are their bodies.</p>
  <p>The mechanism is not mysterious. Statins inhibit HMG-CoA reductase, the enzyme the liver uses to produce cholesterol. That same pathway also synthesizes Coenzyme Q10, a molecule central to cellular energy production in muscle tissue. When CoQ10 synthesis is suppressed — as it is, measurably, in statin users — there are plausible downstream effects on mitochondrial function in muscle cells. This is pharmacology, not speculation. Whether CoQ10 supplementation meaningfully reverses the effect is a separate question, and the evidence there is weak and inconsistent. But the biological mechanism behind statin-associated myalgia is not controversial among those who aren't being paid to contest it.</p>
  <p>The diabetes finding is harder to argue away. A large 2023 cohort study published in <em>JAMA Network Open</em>, funded by the National Institutes of Health, found that statin initiation was associated with a measurably increased risk of new-onset type 2 diabetes — a risk that climbed with higher-intensity therapy. The same HMG-CoA pathway appears to affect insulin sensitivity and pancreatic beta-cell function. A drug partly prescribed to reduce metabolic risk inducing metabolic disease at measurable rates is not a minor footnote. For low-risk primary prevention patients — who are, by definition, not on the brink of a cardiovascular event — it is a legitimate question whether the tradeoff has been honestly characterized.</p>
</section>

<section id="bmj-2024" class="reveal">
  <h2>The 2024 BMJ Study and What It Does to the Standard Argument</h2>
  <p>In 2024, a large cohort study published in <em>The BMJ</em> examined statin use among adults aged 65 and older with no prior atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease. The finding: statin use in this population was not associated with a reduction in all-cause mortality or cardiovascular mortality. Funded by the National Institute on Aging — no pharmaceutical money — this is among the most methodologically independent data points on the table. It is also a cohort study, not a randomized controlled trial, which limits causal inference. That limitation is real and should be stated plainly. But the finding aligns with a pattern that has been accumulating for years: independent studies consistently produce smaller — or null — benefit estimates for low-risk primary prevention than industry-funded analyses do. At some point, a pattern is evidence.</p>
  <p>The standard rebuttal to LDL skepticism in older adults—that lowering LDL is unequivocally causal in atherosclerosis and therefore universally beneficial—holds up better in younger high-risk patients, as seen in trials like the 2019 IMPROVE-IT study, but falters in elderly primary prevention populations per the 2024 BMJ and 2022 JAMA analyses, where higher LDL sometimes correlates with lower mortality in observational data. The 2024 BMJ data is not an outlier in that context—it aligns with other independent studies like the 2019 Cochrane review that found limited benefits in primary prevention for older adults, though industry-backed analyses like the CTT's 2022 meta-analysis claim broader benefits by pooling data that includes higher-risk groups.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-institution" class="reveal">
  <h2>Part II: Why the Numbers Look the Way They Do</h2>
  <p>The evidence in Part I would be unsettling on its own. What makes it a structural problem rather than a scientific disagreement is who produced the countervailing evidence, and under what arrangements.</p>
  <p>The Cholesterol Treatment Trialists' Collaboration is the primary source of pooled statin data globally. Its meta-analyses, published in high-impact journals, are the backbone of international statin guidelines. When physicians cite the 25 to 35 percent relative risk reduction, they are almost always citing CTT-produced or CTT-adjacent analyses. The CTT is primarily funded by grants from Merck, Pfizer, and AstraZeneca — the manufacturers of the drugs it analyzes. This is not an allegation. It is a disclosure statement, published in the papers themselves, read by almost nobody in the consultation room.</p>
  <p>In 2021, the CTT Collaboration published a paper in <em>The Lancet</em> concluding that most muscle symptoms reported by statin users are not actually caused by the drug — the nocebo effect, they argued, accounts for the discrepancy between trial and real-world adverse event rates. The conclusion was widely cited. It was also funded by Merck, Pfizer, AstraZeneca, and others. To be clear about what that means: the companies whose drugs were being exonerated funded the study that exonerated them. The nocebo effect is real — some proportion of reported muscle symptoms in any drug trial reflect expectation rather than pharmacology, and the CTT's finding has a genuine kernel of truth in it. The problem is that this paper was then deployed comprehensively to dismiss the broader adverse event signal, including the data that cannot be explained by expectation alone, including the diabetes data, including the mechanistic CoQ10 story. A paper with a real finding, funded by interested parties, used to launder a broader conclusion. That is not science fraud. It is something subtler and more durable.</p>
</section>

<section id="guidelines-and-conflicts" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Guidelines That Expanded the Market</h2>
  <p>The 2013 AHA/ACC cholesterol guidelines significantly expanded the population of Americans for whom statin therapy was recommended — an expansion that critics noted would add tens of millions of previously untreated patients to the eligible pool. The conflicts of interest among the guideline authors were not hidden; they were disclosed, as required. What the disclosure process does not require is that those conflicts affect the interpretation of those guidelines, or that patients be told about them. Peer-reviewed literature has documented the financial ties between statin guideline authors and statin manufacturers. This is not a fringe claim advanced by functional medicine influencers. It has been published in mainstream medical journals and engaged with by bioethicists who do not have podcasts.</p>
  <p>The institutional story is this: a drug with real, documented efficacy in secondary prevention — patients who have already had a heart attack, patients with established coronary artery disease, patients with diabetes and high cardiovascular risk — gradually had its indicated population expanded through guidelines written by people paid by its manufacturers, justified by relative risk figures that overstate benefit for low-risk patients, while adverse event rates were disputed using studies funded by the same manufacturers. No conspiracy was required. The incentive structure did the work.</p>
</section>

<section id="deprescribing" class="reveal">
  <h2>Deprescribing Is Not Fringe</h2>
  <p>There is a growing clinical movement — documented in peer-reviewed literature, endorsed by geriatricians, and increasingly supported by independent evidence — around deprescribing statins in populations where the benefit-harm calculus has shifted. Older adults who have never had a cardiovascular event are one such population. Patients experiencing significant myalgia who cannot tolerate dose reduction are another. This is not alternative medicine. It is the logical clinical implication of reading the independent evidence carefully and asking, for each patient, whether the number on their absolute risk reduction card actually justifies the number on their adverse event risk card.</p>
  <p>The existence of this movement matters because it tells us something about where the evidence has been pointing for people without financial reasons to look away from it.</p>
</section>

<section id="conclusion" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Informed Consent Actually Requires</h2>
  <p>Statins are not bad drugs. For patients who have had a heart attack, statins save lives — clearly, consistently, across well-conducted trials. For high-risk primary prevention patients — those with diabetes, familial hypercholesterolemia, or a calculated 10-year cardiovascular risk above 10 to 20 percent — the evidence for benefit is substantial and the risk-benefit calculation is genuinely favorable. None of that is in dispute here.</p>
  <p>What is in dispute is what happens in the consultation room when a healthy 55-year-old with a moderately elevated LDL and no other risk factors is handed a statin prescription after a seven-minute appointment. What is in dispute is whether that patient has been told that their absolute risk reduction over a decade may be less than one percentage point. Whether they've been told that real-world rates of muscle symptoms may run to 10 or 15 percent. Whether they've been told that the drug carries a measurable diabetes risk. Whether they've been told that the guideline recommending their prescription was written by researchers some of whom were paid by the drug's manufacturer. Whether they've been told that the largest independent cohort study of people their age found no mortality benefit.</p>
  <p>Informed consent, when the numbers are honest, looks like a physician sitting across from that patient and saying: here is your absolute risk reduction, here is your absolute risk of side effects, here is what the NIA-funded data shows about people your age, and here is what the guideline committee members disclosed receiving last year. Then the patient decides. That is shared decision-making. It requires, as a precondition, that the numbers be presented in a form that serves the patient rather than the market. We are not there yet. The gap between those two things is the story.</p>
</section>

